# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bourbon-whiskey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On February 1, 2025, a trade war started by the United States against Canada and Mexico began when the U.S. president Donald Trump signed orders imposing near-universal tariffs on goods from the two countries entering the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The order called for 25 percent tariffs on all imports from Mexico and all imports from Canada except for oil and energy, which would be taxed at 10 percent.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In response, then Canadian prime minister Justin Trudeau said Canada would retaliate with 25 percent tariffs on CA$30 billion (US$20.6 billion) of American goods, which would expand to CA$155 billion (US$106 billion) after three weeks.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Mexican president Claudia Sheinbaum said Mexico would enact tariffs and non-tariff retaliation against the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On February 3, one day before they were set to take effect, both leaders negotiated a one-month delay for the tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The U.S. tariffs took effect on March 4; Canada's retaliatory tariffs began simultaneously, while Mexico stated it would wait to retaliate.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On March 6, Trump exempted goods compliant with the United States–Mexico–Canada Agreement (USMCA) from tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Later, the U.S. imposed universal tariffs on steel, aluminum, and automotive imports, including those from Mexico and Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Due to the USMCA exemption, as of August 2025, over 85% of Canada-U.S. trade and 84% of Mexico-U.S. trade remains tariff-free.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump has said the tariffs are intended to reduce the U.S.'s trade deficit with Canada and Mexico, force both countries to secure their borders with the U.S. against illegal immigration and fentanyl smuggling, and promote domestic manufacturing in the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Sheinbaum, Trudeau, and Trudeau's successor, Mark Carney, have called the U.S. tariffs unjustified and stated that they violate the USMCA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau said that Trump intends to use tariffs to force Canadian annexation into the United States, which Trump has vehemently suggested.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Economists have said tariffs would likely disrupt trade between the three countries, upending supply chains and increasing consumer prices.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Supreme Court struck down the tariffs the Trump administration implemented on imports from Canada and Mexico under the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in *Learning Resources, Inc. v.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The bilateral trade relationship between the United States and Canada is one of the world's largest.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Canada–U.S. trade comprises about one third of Canada's economy, and about 3 percent of the United States's economy.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In the first nine months of 2024, Canadian government data estimated that CA$800 billion (US$550 billion) of goods crossed the Canada–U.S. border.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] More than 70 percent of Canadian exports go to the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The countries' energy and automotive markets are both highly integrated, and Canada is the U.S.'s largest supplier of both steel and aluminum.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] As of November 2024, the U.S. government estimated the United States's trade deficit with Canada to be US$55 billion.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] This deficit is primarily driven by American demand for Canadian oil; when oil exports are excluded, the U.S. has a trade surplus with Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Roughly 60 percent of oil imported by the U.S. is sourced from Canada, and Canada is the largest supplier of U.S. energy imports and second-largest recipient of U.S. energy exports.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The increased value of U.S. imports from Canada is partially a result of the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022, which created global market instability and raised energy prices.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Cars, trucks, other vehicles, and auto parts constitute 27 percent of Canadian exports to the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Canada is the second-largest source of automobile parts imported to the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The economies of the United States and Mexico are highly intertwined.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In 2024, roughly US$800 billion of goods were transported across the Mexico–U.S. border, and over US$1 billion in commerce between the two countries occurs daily.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In 2023, U.S. exports to Mexico totaled US$322 billion, while the U.S. imported over US$475 billion of Mexican products, according to data from the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] More than 75 percent of Mexico's exports go to the United States, and the U.S. is Mexico's primary trading partner.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Roughly 70 percent of Mexico's natural gas consumption comes from the U.S., and the U.S. imports about 700,000 barrels of crude oil from Mexico each day.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Food production between the two countries is also closely integrated: the U.S. sources roughly half of its fresh fruits and vegetables from Mexico, and Mexico is the top market for U.S. agricultural exports.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Mexico is the third-largest exporter of steel to the U.S., behind only Canada and Brazil; both Mexico and the U.S. have been accused of violating an agreement signed alongside the USMCA to limit steel exports between each other.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Some Americans, including Trump, have said that Mexico has exceeded the level of exports allowed under the agreement.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] At the same time, the Mexican steel organization Canacero reported that the level of U.S. steel exports also breached the deal.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Mexico is the top source of both automobiles and automobile parts imported to the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In 1994, the United States, Canada, and Mexico signed the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), a free trade agreement that eliminated almost all tariffs on trade between the three countries.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] NAFTA has been described as a source of political division.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In the U.S., it caused offshoring as U.S. companies relocated their businesses to Mexico for cheaper labor, harming American factory towns and workers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The backlash against free trade allowed candidates like Donald Trump, who supported protectionist policies, to rise to prominence in U.S. politics.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] However, many parts of the U.S. benefited from NAFTA's increased trade and economic activity.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In 2020, during Trump's first term as U.S. president, NAFTA was replaced by the United States–Mexico–Canada Agreement (USMCA), primarily because Trump disagreed with NAFTA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Changes between NAFTA and the USMCA were largely cosmetic; the new agreement maintained zero tariffs on most products traded across the three countries, but allowed some tariffs to be imposed for national security matters.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The region covered by USMCA is one of the world's largest free trade zones.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] During his first term, Trump threatened tariffs on Mexico if it did not end illegal immigration to the United States across the U.S.–Mexico border and repeatedly threatened to withdraw from NAFTA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump pressured Canada and Mexico to renegotiate NAFTA by threatening aggressive import tariffs, and in May 2018, he extended the U.S.'s global tariffs on steel and aluminum to the two countries, inviting them both to retaliate.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The three countries agreed to lift the steel and aluminum tariffs in May 2019, one year after they had begun, prior to the USMCA taking effect on July 1, 2020.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] One month after the USMCA entered force, Trump said that aluminum imports constituted a national security threat that endangered U.S. producers and imposed 10 percent tariffs on Canadian aluminum.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump ended the tariffs the next month ahead of Canada's planned retaliation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In 2018 and 2019, Trump also placed major tariffs on China, totaling about US$80 billion of tariffs on about US$380 billion of products, which were largely kept in place by the subsequent administration of Joe Biden.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The U.S. government has been concerned over China–Mexico trade, particularly in the automotive sector, because it fears that Chinese companies can use Mexico to export to the United States, circumventing tariffs on China and taking advantage of the USMCA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] From October 2023 to October 2024, U.S. authorities apprehended 23,000 people illegally crossing across its northern border from Canada and 1.5 million people illegally crossing its southern border from Mexico.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump's 2024 presidential campaign outlined an economic strategy that emphasized the use of tariffs to fund proposed tax cuts and encourage domestic manufacturing in the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On December 16, Canada announced a plan to spend CA$1.3 billion (US$913 million) on border security to alleviate Trump's concerns.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The plan included the creation of a joint U.S.–Canada "strike force" intended to combat transnational crime.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On January 6, 2025, Trudeau declared his intention to resign as Liberal Party leader and prime minister after the election of a new leader on March 9.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Doug Ford, the premier of Ontario and head of the Council of the Federation, called a snap provincial election to be held on February 27, saying that he wanted his Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario to have a stronger mandate to oppose Trump's impending tariffs on Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On January 31, Trudeau stated on social media that Canada was "ready with a forceful and immediate response" if the U.S. proceeded with its decision to impose tariffs on Canadian exports.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Since Felipe Calderón's tenure as president of Mexico in 2012, U.S. law enforcement agents based in Mexico were able to collaborate with their Mexican counterparts to gather intelligence, design operations, conduct anti-corruption investigations, and carry out institutional reforms.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] However, in 2019, Andrés Manuel López Obrador began to scale back international cooperation in the Mexican drug war as part of his "Hugs, not bullets" plan.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Opioids, predominantly fentanyl, have killed over 500,000 Americans since 2012.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The opioid epidemic in the United States is largely fueled by drugs smuggled from Mexico; approximately 98 percent of fentanyl entering the U.S. comes from Mexico, while less than 1 percent comes from Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In 2021 and 2022, during the worst years of the opioid epidemic, over 100,000 people in the U.S. died annually from drug overdoses.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In October 2024, Claudia Sheinbaum was inaugurated as president of Mexico.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] She was described as taking "bold moves" against Mexican drug cartels.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump's presidential campaign also pledged the mass deportation of illegal immigrants in the United States—the majority of which are from Mexico.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In response, Mexican officials created an initiative called "Mexico Embraces You" to welcome deported migrants.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] During his inaugural address on January 20, 2025, at the beginning of his second term, Trump said he would enact steep tariffs on other countries.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He said that "Instead of taxing our citizens to enrich other countries", the U.S. would "tariff and tax foreign countries to enrich our citizens".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump said that both Canada and Mexico are allowing "mass numbers of people to come in and fentanyl to come in" to the U.S. across their borders.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Approximately 0.2 percent of fentanyl entering the U.S. comes from Canada, while 98 percent comes from Mexico.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump launched a process to designate Mexican drug cartels and other criminal organizations as foreign terrorist organizations.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He also threatened U.S. military intervention against cartels in Mexico.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump also said both countries were unfairly profiting from the United States's trade deficits.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He has criticized the United States's trade deficit with Canada while citing inaccurate figures that claim it to be as much as US$200 billion.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Even after Trump declared his intention to impose imminent tariffs on Canada and Mexico, U.S. companies did not make a concerted effort to import large quantities of goods to the United States before their enactment.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On January 29, Sheinbaum said of Trump's threatened tariffs that "We don't think its going to happen really", and that "if it happens, we also have our [retaliation] plan", which she declined to detail.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The Mexican foreign ministry said Mexican officials were in talks with the Trump administration.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump also made repeated calls for Canada to be annexed by the United States as its "51st state", and said that while he would not use military coercion, he could use "economic force" to bring about Canadian annexation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Since the trade war began, Trudeau has said that Trump's comments should be taken as a serious threat against Canadian sovereignty and that Trump seeks to control Canada to access its mineral resources.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In an interview, Trump said that his suggestions to annex Canada were serious, and argued that the U.S. trade deficit with Canada was "essentially a subsidy" and that Canada would be "much better off" in the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump has argued that Canadian statehood would make tariffs "totally disappear", lower Canadian taxes, and make the country more secure militarily, and called the Canada–U.S. border an "artificial line that looks like it was done with a ruler".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau has said that Canadian annexation is "never going to happen".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On February 1, 2025, Trump signed three executive orders imposing 25 percent tariffs on all goods from Mexico and Canada except for Canadian oil and energy exports, which received a 10 percent tariff.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Mexican energy exports will be subject to the full 25 percent tariff.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The orders were issued under the International Emergency Economic Powers Act (IEEPA) and were set to take effect at 12:01 a.m.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump also ordered 10 percent tariffs on China, which would be imposed in addition to the existing tariffs of up to 25 percent on many Chinese goods.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The orders included a clause allowing the U.S. to increase its tariffs if the countries respond with their own tariffs or other retaliatory measures.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump used the IEEPA—a 1977 U.S. law giving the president broad financial power during declared national emergencies—to circumvent the USMCA's tariff restriction for reasons other than national security, marking the first time the law was used to impose tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump cited both the influx of illegal immigrants crossing the United States's borders with both Mexico and Canada, as well as the opioid epidemic in the United States fueled by fentanyl originating in China reaching the U.S. through Mexico and Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The tariffs are also aimed at forcing manufacturers to hire Americans to make their products in the U.S. instead of importing them from other countries.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In later remarks, Trump repeated his hope for Canada to be annexed by the United States, and said that it could do so to avoid tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] According to *Bloomberg News*, Trump advisors Peter Navarro and Stephen Miller were the leading officials in the economic discussions regarding the imposition of tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] At the same time, China was included at the urging of the National Security Council.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In a post on Truth Social, Trump said: "We need to protect Americans, and it is my duty as president to ensure the safety of all.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] I made a promise on my campaign to stop the flood of illegal aliens and drugs from pouring across our borders, and Americans overwhelmingly voted in favor of it." While he acknowledged that the tariffs could cause "temporary short-term disruption," he said that they needed to be imposed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Hours after Trump imposed the tariffs on February 1, Trudeau said that Canada would retaliate against the United States with tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He said that Canada would impose 25 percent tariffs on CA$30 billion (US$20.6 billion) of American exports immediately after the U.S. tariffs take effect and impose 25 percent tariffs on a further CA$125 billion (US$86 billion) worth of goods in the next three weeks.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau said that the delay would allow Canadian businesses to prepare.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He added that Canada was considering more retaliatory trade actions in addition to tariffs to force Trump to end the trade war, including export restrictions on critical minerals and energy products, or a ban on American companies bidding on government contracts.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau stated that American liquor, vegetables, clothing, shoes, and perfume would be among the first products to face retaliatory tariffs, and that tariffs would also be imposed on consumer goods such as household appliances, furniture, and sports equipment.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Canada's retaliation is aimed mainly at "red states" of the U.S., led by Trump's Republican Party.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In his speech, Trudeau presented data showing that only about 1 percent of fentanyl imports and illegal border crossings to the United States come from its border with Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He called the U.S.–Canada relationship "the most successful partnership the world has ever seen" across all domains and accused Trump's tariffs of violating the USMCA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He also stated that the tariffs pose a threat to American consumers and industries, urging Canadians to "choose Canadian products and services rather than American ones" whenever possible.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau stated: "This is a choice that, yes, will harm Canadians, but beyond that, it will have real consequences for you, the American people.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Ontario premier Ford said that Canada has "no choice but to hit back and hit back hard" and ordered the Liquor Control Board of Ontario to end sales of American alcohol.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Premier François Legault of Quebec said he ordered Treasury Board president Sonia LeBel to "review all procurement contracts involving American suppliers" and penalize any that do business with Quebec's government.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He also directed the Société des alcools du Québec to remove all American products from its shelves.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Around Christmas time in 2025, multiple Canadian provinces including Nova Scotia and Manitoba announced they would sell shelved American liquor products being kept in storage with profits going to charitable organizations.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] No new liquor was purchased for these fundraisers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In Nova Scotia, Premier Tim Houston said the province will double highway tolls for U.S. vehicles and direct the Nova Scotia Liquor Corporation to stop selling all U.S. liquor by February 4.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Simpson also announced that his government would review its procurement policies to eliminate purchases from U.S. companies where possible.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Premier Wab Kinew of Manitoba and Premier Dennis King of Prince Edward Island both said that their provinces would stop importing American liquor, while British Columbia premier David Eby said the BC Liquor Distribution Branch would halt liquor purchases from Republican-led states.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On March 10, this was then expanded to ban all U.S. alcohol.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Legislation is also planned on being introduced that would tariff U.S. vehicles driving to Alaska through the province.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Yukon premier Ranj Pillai said his territory's government would halt orders of U.S. alcohol, review its contracts with U.S. companies, and consider tolls on U.S. vehicles, but later said the measures would be put on hold until tariffs came into effect.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Pierre Poilievre, the leader of the opposition Conservative Party, condemned what he called "massive, unjust and unjustified tariffs".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He urged that the government end the current prorogation of parliament to retaliate with measures including dollar-for-dollar tariffs on U.S. goods that he said would raise money to help "affected workers and businesses".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He also repeated his demand for a "massive" tax cut and other efforts to bolster the economy.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Sheinbaum had spoken to Trump before his inauguration to de-escalate his tariff threats.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump said that Sheinbaum had agreed to "effectively closing" the Mexico–U.S. border to avoid tariffs; Sheinbaum denied this, but said that "there will not be a potential tariff war".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After Trump signed executive orders imposing 25 percent tariffs, Sheinbaum said Mexico would implement tariff and non-tariff retaliatory measures against the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] She said the retaliation was "in defense of Mexico's interests".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Marcelo Ebrard, Mexico's secretary of economy, called Trump's tariffs a "flagrant violation" of the USMCA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Sheinbaum also responded to Trump's claim that she has an alliance with the Mexican drug cartels, calling it "slander".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] At an event on February 1, she said Mexico would keep a "cool head" in proceeding with its retaliations, and she proposed establishing a task force with the U.S. to address Trump's issues with Mexico and said that "problems are not resolved by imposing tariffs".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On February 3, 2025, Sheinbaum and Trump mutually agreed to delay the tariffs on Mexico by one month, until March 4.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Sheinbaum accepted sending 10,000 troops from the Mexican National Guard to their border to prevent drug trafficking.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump said the U.S. had pledged to take measures to curb weapons trafficking to Mexico.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] During their call, Trump complemented Sheinbaum, telling her "You're tough".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After their call, Sheinbaum directed Mexican law enforcement agencies to target fentanyl gangs, and Mexican police raided opioid labs and arrested cartel members.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On February 27, Mexico transferred 29 cartel operatives, Sinaloa Cartel founding member Rafael Caro Quintero, to the United States to face criminal charges there.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump later described Sheinbaum as "a wonderful woman" with whom he has a "very good" relationship.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump also spoke to Trudeau on February 3.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] During their call, he introduced concerns that Canada was not allowing U.S. banks to "open or do business there"; Canada allows American banks to operate commercially in the country but had restricted personal banking to protect its citizens from bank failure.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The Canadian Bankers Association said that 16 U.S.-based bank subsidiaries and branches with around CA$113 billion (US$78.6 billion) in assets are currently operating in Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After a second call that afternoon, Trump and Trudeau successfully negotiated a one-month delay on the tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Officials present for the call told *The New York Times* and the *Toronto Star* that in addition to concerns over banking, Trump also relayed grievances over Canada's protection of its dairy sector and Canadian consumption taxes that Trump said make American goods more expensive.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump also said that the 1908 treaty between the United States and the United Kingdom that established the 49th parallel as the border between the U.S. and the dominion of Canada was invalid and that he wanted to revise it.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump also mentioned during the call that he wanted to revisit the numerous treaties regulating the sharing of lakes and rivers between the U.S. and Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In addition, he raised Canada's level of defense spending, and questioned whether Canada does "anything" to contribute to the North American Aerospace Defense Command (NORAD), the joint U.S.–Canada air defense command that operates across North America.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau also assured Trump that 10,000 personnel "are and will be" working on border security in Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In response, Trump issued an updated executive order changing the start date of the tariffs to March 4 at 12:01 a.m.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump wrote on social media after the call that he was "very pleased with this initial outcome" and the tariffs had been delayed "to see whether or not a final economic deal with Canada can be structured".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On February 11, Canada appointed Kevin Brosseau, a former deputy national security advisor to Trudeau and former Royal Canadian Mounted Police senior, as the fentanyl czar.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After the call between Trump and Trudeau on February 3, Howard Lutnick, the incoming U.S. secretary of commerce called Dominic LeBlanc, the Canadian finance minister, who he had been communicating regularly since December 2024.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Lutnick said that Trump had realized the U.S.–Canada relationship was governed by a series of agreements that could be quickly abandoned.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] He said Trump was interested in dissolving arrangements related to sharing and managing the Great Lakes, and reviewing military cooperation between the two countries, including NORAD.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Lutnick also said Trump wanted to remove Canada from the Five Eyes, an intelligence-sharing alliance between the U.S., Canada, United Kingdom, Australia, and New Zealand; the *Financial Times* reported that some officials in Trump's administration have sought to remove Canada from the alliance.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Marco Rubio, the U.S. secretary of state, dismissed that the U.S. was reconsidering military cooperation with Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] However, Canadian officials, despite initially believing Trump's suggestion of annexing Canada into the United States to be a joke, began to interpret it as a serious threat.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On February 10, 2025, Trump imposed 25 percent tariffs on steel and aluminum entering the United States from all countries, including Canada and Mexico, which provide most of the U.S.'s metal imports.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The steel and aluminum tariffs are set to enter force on March 12.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump said those tariffs were "the first of many", and that over the next four weeks, he would discuss tariffs on cars, pharmaceuticals, chips, and other goods with his team.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] In response, Trudeau called the tariffs "unacceptable" and said he hoped talks with the Trump administration would resolve the issue, but that Canada will have a "firm and clear" response if needed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Shares of U.S. steelmakers rose in response to Trump's order, while prices for steel and aluminum rose.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On March 3, Trump said that the tariffs that were delayed from February would take effect as planned on March 4, and that there was "no room left" for Canada or Mexico to negotiate a last-minute deal with the United States to delay them further.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Lutnick said that both Canada and Mexico had made progress on improving border security, but that neither had satisfied the U.S.'s demands to halt the flow of fentanyl into the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Canadian foreign minister Mélanie Joly said that Canada was prepared to respond, while Sheinbaum reaffirmed that Mexico's prior response plans would take effect when Trump's tariffs were imposed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] U.S. tariffs on Canada and Mexico began as scheduled, at 12:01 a.m.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Canada's retaliation began simultaneously: 25 percent tariffs on CA$30 billion (US$20.6 billion) of U.S. goods took effect on March 4, and Trudeau affirmed that 25 percent tariffs on an additional CA$125 billion (US$86 billion) of U.S. goods would take effect 21 days later, on March 25.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau called Trump's decision to impose tariffs "very dumb", and said Canada would "not back down from a fight".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The onset of the tariffs led to stock market declines in the U.S., especially for retailers and car manufacturers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] On March 5, Lutnick said Trump was "listening to the offers from Mexico and Canada" and "thinking about trying to do something in the middle", suggesting that tariffs could take effect at a less significant scale.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Later that day, Trump granted a one-month exception from the tariffs for automakers compliant with USMCA regulations, which represent about 85 percent of passenger vehicles imported to the U.S. from Mexico in 2024.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump decided after meeting with executives from the three largest U.S. automakers—Ford, General Motors, and Stellantis—who said that the tariffs would harm U.S. companies more than their foreign rivals.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After the U.S. tariffs took effect on March 4, Sheinbaum said she would announce Mexico's countermeasures, including retaliatory tariffs, on March 9.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] She cited plans to speak with Trump in the intervening days as the reason for her delayed response.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Sheinbaum said that if the tariffs persisted, Mexico would "reach out to Canada and other nations" and could look for trading partners other than the U.S. or shift trade alliances "if necessary".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trump and Sheinbaum spoke by phone on March 6.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Sheinbaum began the call by listing to Trump her efforts to secure the Mexico–U.S. border and fight fentanyl trafficking, suggesting to him that the tariffs would make it more difficult for her to justify cooperation with the U.S. to a domestic audience.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] She sent Trump a chart showing how fentanyl seizures at the border had dropped dramatically since the 10,000 National Guard troops had arrived.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] During the call, Trump complimented Sheinbaum and asked her opinion of Trudeau, calling her "lucky" after she responded that they rarely talked.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] While Sheinbaum recounted that Trump initially refused to lift tariffs, by the end of their call Trump offered exclusions for many Mexican goods.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After speaking to Sheinbaum, Trump posted on social media that he would delay tariffs on all USMCA-compliant goods until April 2 "out of respect" for Sheinbaum, and thanked her for her "hard work and cooperation".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Immediately afterward, Sheinbaum wrote on Twitter that she and Trump had an "excellent and respectful" call and thanked Trump, saying the two had "agreed that our work and collaboration have yielded unprecedented results".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Trudeau and Trump had spoken by phone on March 5, and Trump said their conversation ended on a "somewhat 'friendly'" note.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After Sheinbaum's call, Trump extended the delay of tariffs on USMCA-compliant products to Canada on March 6.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] After Trump's announcement, Canadian officials said that the planned increases in their retaliatory tariffs would be suspended, though the initial tariffs on the U.S. would remain in place.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Although only about 50 percent of U.S. imports from Mexico and 38 percent of U.S. imports from Canada were USMCA-compliant in 2024, many companies had not filed the requisite paperwork because previous tariff levels were so low.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] Both Canada and Mexico believed that nearly all of their exports would be quickly made compliant.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p01] The Royal Bank of Canada estimated that almost 90% of Canadian exports entered the U.S. duty free in April 2025, and by August said 100% of Canadian energy exports and 95% of other exports were compliant with the trade pact.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 7, Trump threatened reciprocal tariffs on Canadian lumber and dairy products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] He said the tariffs would be as high as about 250 percent and take effect the following week.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Since U.S. dairy exports to Canada have never exceeded the quota, the Canadian tariffs have never been activated.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 9, the day Sheinbaum had planned to announce Mexico's retaliation, she held an event in Mexico City's central plaza to celebrate the delay on the U.S. tariffs, which tens of thousands of Mexicans attended.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Sheinbaum said during the event that "Fortunately, dialogue and respect have prevailed" and they she was optimistic that Mexico would not be given further tariffs and that she would negotiate with Trump with a "cool head".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Beginning on March 10, Ontario imposed a 25 percent surcharge on electricity exports to the U.S. states of Michigan, Minnesota, and New York.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The next day, Trump said that Canada would face 50 percent tariffs on steel and aluminum on March 12, rather than the 25 percent tariffs imposed on every other country.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Ford said that afternoon that he would suspend the surcharge on electricity exports, saying "The temperature needs to come down." In response, Trump said that the U.S. would only impose 25 percent tariffs on Canadian steel and aluminum.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 13, the day after those tariffs entered force, Canada imposed 25 percent tariffs on an additional CA$29 billion (US$20 billion) of U.S. goods.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In a joint statement, Ford and Lutnick said that U.S. and Canadian officials would meet in Washington, D.C., on March 13 to discuss a "renewed USMCA".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 9, Mark Carney won the Liberal Party leadership election to succeed Trudeau as Canadian prime minister.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump pledged to impose "reciprocal" tariffs on all countries beginning in April 2.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In response, Carney said that "it clear that the United States is no longer a reliable partner", and that while "it is possible that, with comprehensive negotiations, we will be able to restore some trust", "there will be no turning back" in the Canada–U.S. relationship.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney and Trump spoke directly for the first time in a phone call on March 28.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney called the call "very cordial" and "substantial", and said that Trump "respected Canada's sovereignty".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump described his call as "extremely productive" and said that he and Carney "agree on many things".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump referred to Carney as the "prime minister of Canada", whereas he had addressed Trudeau as the "governor" of Canada as a U.S. state.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In addition, Trump said that he believes "things will work out very well between Canada and the United States".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney told Trump that Canada would respond with retaliatory tariffs if the U.S. tariffs planned for April 2 came into effect.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Both leaders agreed to start "comprehensive negotiations about a new economic and security relationship" between Canada and the U.S. after the Canadian federal election on April 28.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On April 2, when Trump imposed universal 10 percent tariffs on imports from all countries, Canada and Mexico were exempted; the countries faced no new tariffs from the U.S. and the exemption given to most USMCA-compliant goods was extended indefinitely.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Senate narrowly approved a measure that would revoke some of Trump's tariffs on Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Four senators from the Republican Party (Susan Collins, Lisa Murkowski, Rand Paul and Mitch McConnell) joined all senators of the opposition Democratic Party in passing the resolution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] However, the measure also needs to pass the Republican-controlled House of Representatives to take effect, in which Republican leaders have much more power to block said measure.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Sheinbaum said that Mexico had been given "preferential treatment" by the U.S. and that Canada and Mexico had avoided additional tariffs because of the USMCA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] She added that U.S. and Mexican officials had a "mutual respect" relationship.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Mexican economy secretary Ebrard said that the worldwide U.S. tariffs could help Mexico by making it cheaper to do business there relative to other countries.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Despite Canada's exclusion, Carney denounced the tariffs and said they would "rupture the global economy" and harm economic growth.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] He also said he would seek to assemble a "coalition of like-minded countries" to create an alternative to the U.S., and that "if the United States no longer wants to lead, Canada will".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] He declared: "The 80-year period when the United States embraced the mantle of global economic leadership, when it forged alliances rooted in trust and mutual respect and championed the free and open exchange of goods and services, is over.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump announced universal 25 percent tariffs on automobiles and automobile parts on March 27, which came into effect on April 3.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] When the U.S. tariffs began, Carney announced that Canada would retaliate with a 25 percent tariff on U.S. cars and trucks imported into Canada and that Canada would use the money generated from the tariffs to support people and businesses negatively impacted by U.S. tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Sheinbaum said that the U.S. auto export tariffs were a concern for Mexico and that she hoped to continue speaking to U.S. officials to lower tariffs on auto exports, steel, and aluminum.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Rather than retaliating with tariffs, however, Sheinbaum announced that Mexico would try to mitigate the impact of the tariffs by increasing domestic production of corn, beans, and rice, in addition to fuel and refined oil products to reduce its dependence on U.S. natural gas.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On April 11, Trump threatened Mexico with further tariffs and sanctions, saying that it was violating its obligation under the 1944 treaty between the two countries relating to water resources in the Tijuana, Colorado, and Rio Grande rivers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Despite the treaty requiring that Mexico deliver to the United States 1.75 million acre-feet of water every five years, it had offered less than 500,000 from October 2020 to December 2024.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump accused Mexico of "stealing the water from Texas farmers".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Sheinbaum acknowledged that Mexico had failed to fulfill its commitments under the treaty: She said that the 2020–2023 North American drought had prevented Mexico from providing the full amount of water, but that "to the extent of water availability, Mexico has been complying".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Sheinbaum said that Mexico had sent "a comprehensive proposal" to the U.S. to resolve the issue, and said that "I am sure that, as in other matters, an agreement will be reached".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney led the Liberal Party to victory in the April 28 Canadian federal election, with the party winning enough seats to form a minority government.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney had campaigned on a promise to stand up to Trump's threats and protect Canada's economy; after winning, he declared: "Trump is trying to break us so he can own us.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] That will never happen." The day after the election, Trump called Carney to congratulate him on his victory; in a news conference on May 2, Carney said he and Trump had agreed to travel and meet in Washington, D.C., on May 6.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney met Trump at the White House on May 6.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney characterized the meeting, which was two hours long and included a 75-minute one-on-one meeting between the two leaders, as "very positive", and Trump said it went "very well" with "no tension".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump largely refrained from criticizing Carney or Canada, calling Canada "a very special place" to him and responded to a reporter's question about what "concession" he wanted from Canada by saying he only sought "friendship".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Speaking to reporters at the Canadian Embassy in Washington after the meeting, Carney said that during the meeting Canada "began the renegotiation of our trading relationship" with the U.S. and that Trump had committed to negotiate a new Canada–U.S. trade agreement.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] During their meeting, Trump and Carney also discussed foreign policy issues such as the Russia–Ukraine war, the Middle Eastern crisis, and China.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney said he told Trump that it was not "useful" for him to continue referring to Canada as the "51st state" and threatening annexation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] After the meeting, Trump echoed Carney's statement that the meeting set Canada–U.S. relations on a better trajectory and called Carney "a big step up" as a leader, criticizing Trudeau and former deputy prime minister Chrystia Freeland.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney said he and Trump would meet next at the 51st G7 summit in June, which Canada hosted in Kananaskis, Alberta.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] By May 14, 2025, consulting group Oxford Economics estimated that Canada had "effectively suspended almost all of its retaliatory tariffs on U.S. products" following the exemptions implemented a month prior.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Minister of Finance François-Philippe Champagne called this a "falsehood", and stated that 70 percent of the tariffs were still in place.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On June 4, U.S. steel and aluminum tariffs doubled to 50 percent.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney said Canada was in intense negotiations with the U.S. but preparing reprisals if they failed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Bea Bruske, president of the Canadian Labour Congress, stated 23,000 steel jobs and another 9,500 aluminum jobs would be impacted within days.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] At the G7 summit on June 16, the two countries pledged to work on a deal with the next 30 days.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In a June 20 press conference, Carney said Canada would increase its counter-tariffs on steel and aluminium products, at the time 25%, on July 21 if talks with the United States stalled.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Carney invited Sheinbaum to the G7 summit, though Trump departed the summit early on June 15 to deal with the Twelve-Day War, missing a scheduled meeting between him and Sheinbaum.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On June 27, U.S. president Donald Trump announced the suspension of the trade talks with Canada, also announcing new tariffs on goods crossing the Canada–United States border.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On July 11, Trump announced in a letter sent to Carney that the US would raise the tariffs to 35%, starting August 1.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] He cited the retaliatory tariffs imposed by Canada against the US as the main reason, as well as the continued flow of fentanyl into the US from Canada and the trade deficit with Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On August 5, the Associated Press reported that due to the USMCA exemption, as of August 2025, over 85% of Canada-U.S. trade and 84% of Mexico-U.S. trade remains tariff-free.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On August 22, Carney announced Canada would drop many of their retaliatory tariffs by matching the USMCA exemption in order to jump start trade talks.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] "Canada currently has the best trade deal with the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] And while it’s different from what we had before, it’s still better than that of any other country," said Carney.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On October 23, Trump announced that all trade negotiations with Canada were canceled after the Ontario government published a public service announcement with audio clips of former US president Ronald Reagan stating that tariffs on foreign goods are poor policy in the long term.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump later said he would raise tariffs on Canada by "more than 10%" in response to the advertisement.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump said the bridge's opening will be delayed until multiple trade and bridge related grievances were resolved.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump's announcement was criticised by politicians, business leaders and industry groups.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The United States tariffs and threats against Canada have harmed historically strong Canada–U.S. relations, caused increases in Canadian nationalism and patriotism, and led to an uptick in anti-Americanism.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] An Ipsos poll in February 2025 found that, after Trump's threats, 68 percent of Canadians thought less of the United States, while 65 percent said they would avoid traveling to the U.S. and 67 percent said they would avoid buying U.S.-made products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The same month, a Léger poll found that 27 percent of Canadians considered the U.S. an "enemy", while only 1 percent of Americans thought the same of Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In the days after the initial tariff announcements, Canadian crowds booed the U.S. national anthem at sporting events featuring American teams.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Many Canadians began a boycott of American goods and travel to the United States and a "Buy Canadian" movement gained traction across the country.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] As prime minister, Trudeau supported the Canadian boycott.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Many Canadian politicians, including Trudeau and Poilievre, spoke of national unity, and the trade war and conflict with the U.S. created a rally 'round the flag effect in the lead-up to the 2025 Canadian federal election.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Both Canadians across the political spectrum and Canadian society at large have grown concerned over threats from the United States; Canadian politicians have a motive to "push back immediately and forcefully" against Trump and the U.S. because of the threats to Canadian sovereignty.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The trade war also increased support for the removal of trade barriers between Canada's provinces, which Trudeau said that all premiers support but that "challenges within bureaucracies" persist.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Simultaneously, Alberta premier Danielle Smith pledged to hold a referendum on Albertan separatism in 2026 if enough voters sign a petition in favor of doing so.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Whereas in early January 2025, the Liberals had trailed the Conservatives in federal election opinion polls by over 20 points for months, the party began to close the gap in polls after the trade war began and Trudeau announced his resignation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Support for the New Democratic Party and Bloc Québécois also fell dramatically, and polling suggested a close race between the Carney-led Liberals and the Poilievre-led Conservatives.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In February 2025, following Trump's initial announcement, Canadian travel to the United States dropped by 40 percent compared to February 2024.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] A March 2025 *Abacus Data* poll found that 62 percent of Canadians planned to avoid traveling to the U.S. for the next year, and American tourism groups are worried they will lose Canadian tourist traffic.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The mayor of Haines, Alaska, a town connected to the outside world only through Yukon, has expressed concern that the tariffs will affect the normally friendly relations between Americans and Canadians.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The shift in Canadian travel away from the U.S. could amount to an annual loss of US$4 billion for the U.S. economy.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In March 2025, the Trump administration said that beginning on April 11, 2025, Canadians entering the U.S. for more than 30 days are required to register with authorities and be fingerprinted.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The tariffs could affect negotiations on renewing the USMCA, for which a review is due in 2026.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump has ordered U.S. officials to review and report how to correct "unfair" trade practices by April 1, 2025.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Canadian officials have grown concerned that Trump may threaten tariffs to force changes to the agreement.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In the United States, a February 2025 survey by The Harris Poll for *Bloomberg News* found that around 60 percent of Americans believe that high tariffs could cause consumer prices to rise.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The following month, a poll by the University of Michigan found that the number of Americans expressing confidence in the economy fell by 11 percent in March 2025, and that the number expecting inflation rose.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Many Americans believe Trump's threats to annex Canada are a joke or a negotiation strategy, and Trump's tariff policy in general raised questions about whether he has a serious intent to impose tariffs or whether his orders to impose them are threats intended only to serve as a negotiation tactic.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The imposition and rollback of tariffs created uncertainty for many businesses, and has led to an erosion of international confidence in the U.S. as a reliable trade partner.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] According to *Deutsche Welle,* Trump's imposition of tariffs on Canada and Mexico violated both the USMCA and the rules of the World Trade Organization (WTO), of which all three countries are members.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 13, 2025, the WTO said that Canada had formally requested to begin dispute resolution proceedings with the United States, saying that the tariffs violated the U.S.'s commitments under the 1994 General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On April 7, Canada also initiated WTO dispute resolution proceedings regarding the U.S. tariffs on cars and car parts.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In Mexico, the government and local businesses aimed to bolster a "Made in Mexico" campaign to promote domestic products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Some Mexicans called for boycotts of U.S. products after Trump's initial threat of tariffs, and a poll by the Mexican firm Buendía & Márquez found that 80 percent of Mexicans held a negative opinion of Trump in mid-February 2025, an increase from 66 percent in early January.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Sheinbaum's approval rating also rose, with some polls in February 2025 suggesting that it exceeds 80 percent.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The European Commission—the executive branch of the European Union—condemned U.S. tariffs on Canada and Mexico, and called for the U.S. to "reconsider its approach".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In February 2026, the United States House of Representatives voted to repeal the tariffs that had been imposed on Canadian goods during Donald Trump's administration.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The resolution passed by a 219–211 vote, with a small number of Republican lawmakers joining nearly all Democrats in support.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The tariffs had originally been enacted under a national emergency declaration in February 2025, and their repeal represented a rare bipartisan rebuke of Trump's trade policy.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Following the vote, President Trump reportedly threatened political consequences for Republicans who voted against the measure.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] While passage in the House reflects congressional concern over the tariffs, actual repeal would still require Senate approval and presidential assent, and was expected to face a potential veto.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The trade war led investors to fear that tariffs could create inflation by causing rises in both manufacturing costs and consumer prices, leading to volatility in the U.S. stock market.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Trump has characterized the economy as being in "period of transition" for the start of his presidency.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] By March 6, the S&P 500 had lost almost all of its gains since November 2024.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 9, Trump declined to say whether his policies could lead to a recession in the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] He said in an interview with *Fox News* that it would take time to see the payoff from his policies, but that they would ultimately be worthwhile, saying "If you look at China, they have a 100-year perspective.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] We go by quarters, and you can't go by that.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] You have to do what's right." The next day, the S&P 500 dropped an additional 2.7 percent—its largest single-day drop of 2025—and the Nasdaq by 4 percent.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 10, the S&P 500 fell by 1.4 percent, pushing it into a correction, which is defined as a fall in a stock market index of over 10 percent from its peak; the S&P 500 was 10.1 percent lower than its record high, which was on February 19.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The market's losses were equivalent to over US$4 trillion in value; the Nasdaq-100 and Russell 2000 indices had already entered corrections.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] On March 11, the S&P 500 rose by 2.1 percent, exiting a correction, though ending the week down 2.3 percent.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] After Trump's April 2 tariffs, the S&P 500 fell over 10 percent in two days, in its worst week since the COVID-19 recession of 2020.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] In Canada and Mexico, stock markets were more stable.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] By March 6, Mexico's most prominent stock market index, the Índice de Precios y Cotizaciones, had risen 6 percent since the beginning of 2025.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Canada's benchmark index, the S&P/TSX, was almost the same level it began the year.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The trade war is expected to significantly disrupt trade between the United States, Mexico, and Canada and upend supply chains across North America.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Many economists have expressed skepticism over the effectiveness of Trump's strategy in imposing tariffs, and many have said that increased tariffs would raise the prices of consumer goods in the U.S. and worsen the country's cost-of-living crisis.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The Budget Lab at Yale University estimated that the tariffs would lead to a loss of about US$1,200 in purchasing power for the typical American household.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] While some companies will opt to bear the cost of the tariff, others are likely to raise prices on consumer products to offset lost revenue or attempt to negotiate lower prices for their products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Because the United States does not produce enough oil to satisfy its demand, 10 percent tariffs on Canadian oil and energy will likely lead to an increased oil price across the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] This is especially true in the Midwest, a region heavily reliant on oil imported from Alberta.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The Canadian government had previously said that U.S. gas prices could increase by US$0.75 per gallon overnight if tariffs were imposed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Tariffs could also increase the cost of electricity in some U.S. states, especially those that rely on Canadian provinces like Ontario, Quebec, and British Columbia for energy.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Outside North America, tariffs on energy imports would give European and Asian oil refineries a competitive advantage against their rivals.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The tariffs could also lead to price increases in various U.S. imports from Mexico and Canada, including fruits, vegetables, beer, liquor, and electronics from Mexico and potatoes, grains, lumber, and steel from Canada.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Price increases would compound with high inflation in the U.S., especially in grocery prices.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The cost of Canadian lumber, used by many homebuilders in the U.S., would also likely increase.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The tariffs would also cause risk to the U.S. farming and fishing industries.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The tariffs pose a risk of "severe recession" in Mexico if maintained.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] A year-long 25 percent tariff could cause Mexican exports to fall by around 12 percent, ultimately leading to a 4 percent decline in the country's gross domestic product in 2025.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The American Chamber of Commerce in Mexico, the group representing U.S. companies in the country, said tariffs would harm both economies and "fail to address the real challenges of security, migration and drug trafficking".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The Mexican automobile industry is likely to be most susceptible to upheaval from the tariffs, alongside the electric equipment sector, making it the largest beneficiary of the reprieve given to USMCA-compliant car imports.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Canada, a highly trade-dependent economy, will also likely suffer, experiencing harmed economic growth and increased prices for businesses and consumers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] The Canadian economy could enter a recession within six months if the tariffs are maintained.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Quebec premier Legault said that the U.S. tariffs could cause the loss of as many as 100,000 Canadian jobs within the province.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Prices could also increase in Canada for even domestically produced products, mainly if the tariffs cause economic difficulties for smaller businesses.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Canadian companies being unable to sell their products to Americans at the same volume would also cause some of them to cut workers, scale back, or even shut down entirely.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/2025-united-states-trade-war-with-canada-and-mexico-p02] Canada's mineral processing industry will likely be significantly harmed by the tariffs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Acaçá is the only ritual food required in Candomblé; it is offered to all the orixás in the Candomblé pantheon.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Acaçá made of white corn is offered to Oxala; that made of yellow corn is offered to Oxossi.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Acaçá is made of white or red corn soaked in water for a day, which is then passed through a mill to make a paste or dough.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] The paste or dough is cooked in a pan and stirred continuously to reach a correct consistency.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] While warm, small portions of the dough are wrapped in a clean, folded clean banana leaf and passed over a fire.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Finely ground white cornmeal can be substituted for soaked corn.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] The acaçá is cut into pieces of equal size.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] They are arranged on a platter to be placed on or near a *pegi*, or Candomblé altar.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] They also decorate other ritual foods in Candomblé, notably vatapá.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto (Portuguese: *acaçá of black beans*) is a variation of the acaçá made from black beans, i.e., the black turtle bean (*Phaseolus vulgaris*).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Black beans are substituted for soaked corn, similarly made into a paste, wrapped in banana leaves, and steamed in a pan.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto is specifically offered to the god Ogum.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] The variation of acaçá is associated with Casa Fanti Ashanti, a Candomblé temple of the Jeje-Nagô tradition in the neighborhood of Cruzeiro do Anil, São Luís, in the state of Maranhão.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Acaçá de leite (transl. acaçá of milk) is a fermented drink used in Candomblé rituals.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] It is made from a corn mush to which milk and other seasonings are added.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] Acaçá de leite is found in Candomblé temples in Bahia and the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] A variation, acaçá de leite de coco, is made from coconut milk.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acaçá] This variation is found in the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Although bourbon may be made anywhere in the U.S., it is associated with the Southern United States, particularly Kentucky, through a history of advertising bourbon as a product of Kentucky with rural, Southern origins.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Thanks to a market shift in the 1990s, it has also become a symbol of urbanization and sophistication, with a large consumer demographic belonging to the middle- to upper-class, including business and community leaders.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] After World War II, a boom in bourbon consumption and exports occurred.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon was recognized in 1964 by the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Congress as a "distinctive product of the United States." Bourbon sold in the U.S. must be produced within the U.S. from at least 51% corn and stored in a new container of charred oak.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon has been distilled since the 18th century.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] As of 2014, distillers' wholesale market revenue for bourbon sold within the U.S. was about $2.7 billion, and bourbon made up about two thirds of the $1.6 billion of U.S. exports of distilled spirits.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] According to the Distilled Spirits Council of the United States, in 2018 U.S. distillers derived $3.6 billion in revenue from bourbon and Tennessee whiskey (a closely related spirit produced in the state of Tennessee).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Distilling was most likely brought to present-day Kentucky in the late 18th century by Scots, Scots-Irish, and other settlers (including English, Irish, Welsh, German, and French) who began to farm the area.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The origin of bourbon as a distinct form of whiskey is not well documented and there are many conflicting legends and claims.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In Bourbon County, across the county line from Craig's distillery in what was then Fayette County, an early distiller named Jacob Spears has been named as the first to label his product as Bourbon whiskey.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Although still popular and often repeated, the Craig legend is apocryphal.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Similarly, the Spears story is a local favorite but is rarely repeated outside the county.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] There likely was no single "inventor" of bourbon, which developed into its present form in the late 19th century.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Essentially, any type of grain can be used to make whiskey, and the practice of aging whiskey and charring the barrels for better flavor had been known in Europe for centuries.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The late date of the Bourbon County etymology has led historian Michael Veach to dispute its authenticity.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] He proposes the whiskey was named after Bourbon Street in New Orleans, a major port where shipments of Kentucky whiskey sold well as a cheaper alternative to French cognac.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Another proposed origin of the name is the association with the geographic area known as *Old Bourbon*, consisting of the original Bourbon County in Virginia organized in 1785.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] This region included much of today's Eastern Kentucky, including 34 of the modern counties.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It included the current Bourbon County in Kentucky, which became a county when Kentucky separated from Virginia as a new state in 1792.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Numerous newspaper articles reference whiskey from Bourbon County, Kentucky dating as far back as 1824.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] According to the whiskey writer Charles K.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Although many distilleries operated in Bourbon County historically, no distilleries operated there between 1919 and late 2014, when a small distillery opened – a period of 95 years.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] A refinement often dubiously credited to James C.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Crow is the sour mash process, which conditions each new fermentation with some amount of spent mash.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Spent mash is also known as *spent beer*, *distillers' spent grain*, *stillage*, and *slop* or *feed mash*, so named because it is used as animal feed.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The acid introduced when using the sour mash controls the growth of bacteria that could taint the whiskey and creates a proper pH balance for the yeast to work.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Prohibition devastated the bourbon industry.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] With the ratification of the 18th amendment in 1919, all distilleries were forced to stop operating.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Six companies were granted permits to bottle medicinal whiskey from existing stocks: A.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Stitzel Distillery (later called the Stitzel–Weller Distillery), American Medicinal Spirits (producer of Old Crow and Old Grand-Dad, sold in 1929 to National Distillers, now owned by Suntory Global Spirits), Brown-Forman (still a current major producer), Frankfort Distillery (including the George T.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Stagg distillery now called the Buffalo Trace Distillery and owned by Sazerac), James Thompson and Brothers (later called Glenmore Distillery, now owned by Sazerac), and Schenley Distillery (now owned by Guinness).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Prescriptions were required to buy medicinal whiskey.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In 1928 when stocks ran out, the US government allowed a 100-day "Distillers' Holiday" to the select distillers to replenish the medicinal stock.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Production was shut down completely again in 1941 to reserve production capacity for making industrial alcohol during World War II.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Kyle Romero, after World War II, whiskey transitioned from a primarily domestic product to a major export product.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The war introduced many American soldiers to whiskey, and veterans boosted a growing domestic demand.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The postwar economic boom and the rise of consumer culture fueled whiskey's golden age in the 1950s and 1960s, solidifying its place in global markets.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The Bourbon Institute, established in 1958, played a crucial role in reducing trade restrictions, particularly in Europe, further expanding whiskey's international reach.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] By 1960, the institute explicitly framed bourbon as a cultural ambassador of American identity, reinforcing the idea that its global presence reflected the broader influence of American ways and products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] A U.S. federal regulation now restricts the definition of *bourbon* for whiskey to only include spirits produced in the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In recent years, bourbon and Tennessee whiskey, which is sometimes regarded as a different type of spirit but generally meets the legal requirements to be called bourbon, have enjoyed significant growth in popularity.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The industry trade group Distilled Spirits Council of the United States (DISCUS) tracks sales of bourbon and Tennessee whiskey together.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] According to DISCUS, during 2009–2014, the number of 9-liter cases of whiskey sold increased by 28.5% overall.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Higher-end bourbon and whiskeys experienced the greatest growth.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Gross supplier revenues (including federal excise tax) for U.S. bourbon and Tennessee whiskey increased by 46.7% over the 2009–2014 period, with the greatest growth coming from high-end products.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In 2014, more than 19 million nine-liter cases of bourbon and Tennessee whiskey were sold in the U.S., generating almost $2.7 billion in wholesale distillery revenue.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] U.S. exports of bourbon whiskey surpassed $1 billion for the first time in 2013; distillers hailed the rise of a "golden age of Kentucky bourbon" and predicted further growth.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In 2014, it was estimated that U.S. bourbon whiskey exports surpassed $1 billion, making up the majority of the U.S. total of $1.6 billion in spirits exports.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Major export markets for U.S. spirits are, in descending order: Canada, the United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and France.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The largest percentage increases in U.S. exports were, in descending order: Brazil, the Dominican Republic, Bahamas, Israel, and United Arab Emirates.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Key elements of growth in the markets showing the largest increases have been changes of law, trade agreements, and reductions of tariffs, as well as increased consumer demand for premium-category spirits.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] During the second Trump administration, international sales of bourbon decreased significantly as importing countries curtailed their purchases.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Provinces in Canada, which until the trade war and annexation threats had comprised 10% of Kentucky's whiskey business, stopped selling American products in government-owned liquor stores.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] This led to a contraction in the bourbon business, with multiple distilleries filing for bankruptcy.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Overall exports of American spirits, bourbon included, fell 9% between 2024 and 2025.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] By early 2026, despite the contraction in exports, the industry's total economic impact in Kentucky reached a record US$10.6 billion, according to the Kentucky Distillers' Association.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] This growth has been met with significant logistical hurdles, specifically in the management of a record 16.1 million aging barrels, necessitating a rapid expansion of bonded warehouse (rickhouse) infrastructure across the state.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] To mitigate inventory imbalances caused by global trade volatility, some major producers implemented production pauses in 2026, most notably at Jim Beam's Clermont facility.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon's legal definition varies somewhat from country to country, but many trade agreements require that the name "bourbon" be reserved for products made in the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The U.S. regulations for labeling and advertising bourbon apply only to products made for consumption within the U.S.; they do not apply to distilled spirits made for export.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Canadian law requires products labeled bourbon to be made in the U.S. and to conform to the requirements that apply within the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The European Union also requires bourbon to be made in the U.S. following the law of the country.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] However, in other countries, products labeled bourbon may not adhere to the same standards.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] For example, U.S.-produced products with somewhat lower alcohol content than the level required in the United States can be sold in Australia as bourbon, with Cougar Bourbon being an example of an export-only brand produced in the U.S. for the Australia market.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon has no minimum specified duration for its aging period.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Products aged for as little as three months are sold as bourbon.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The exception is straight bourbon, which has a minimum aging requirement of two years.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In addition, any bourbon aged less than four years must include an age statement on its label.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon that meets the above requirements, has been aged for a minimum of two years, and does not have added coloring, flavoring, or other spirits may be – but is not required to be – called straight bourbon.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bottled in bond bourbon is a sub-category of straight bourbon that must be produced by a single distiller at a single distillery in a single season, aged at least four years in a bonded warehouse under federal control, and bottled at 100 proof (50% ABV).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon that is labeled *blended* (or as a *blend*) may contain added coloring, flavoring, and other spirits, such as un-aged neutral grain spirits, but at least 51% of the product must be straight bourbon.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] "High rye bourbon" is not a legally defined term but usually means a bourbon with 20–35% rye in its mash bill.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] High-wheat or "wheated" bourbons are described as more mild and subdued compared to high-rye varieties.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon that has been aged for less than three years cannot legally be referred to as whiskey (or whisky) in the European Union.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Congress declared bourbon whiskey as a "distinctive product of the United States" by concurrent resolution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon may be produced anywhere in the U.S. where it is legal to distill spirits, but most brands are produced in Kentucky, where bourbon production has a strong historical association.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The filtering of iron-free water through the high concentrations of limestone that are unique to the area is often touted by bourbon distillers in Kentucky as a signature step in the bourbon-making process.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Senate passed a resolution sponsored by Senator Jim Bunning (R-KY) officially declaring September 2007 to be National Bourbon Heritage Month, commemorating the history of bourbon whiskey.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Notably, the resolution claimed that Congress had declared bourbon to be "America's Native Spirit" in its 1964 resolution.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] However, the 1964 resolution did not contain such a statement; it declared bourbon to be a distinctive product identifiable with the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] (in a similar way that Scotch is considered identifiable with Scotland).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The resolution was passed again in 2008.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] As of 2018, 95% of all bourbon is produced in Kentucky, according to the Kentucky Distillers' Association.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] As of 2018, there were 68 whiskey distilleries in Kentucky, this was up 250 percent in the past ten years.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] At that time, the state had more than 8.1 million barrels of bourbon that were aging.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] By October 2025, the inventory reached an all-time high of 16.1 million aging barrels, according to the Kentucky Distillers' Association.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bardstown, Kentucky, is home to the annual Bourbon Festival held each September.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It has been called the "Bourbon Capital of the World" by the Bardstown Tourism Commission and the Kentucky Bourbon Festival organizers who have registered the phrase as a trademark.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Tennessee is home to other major bourbon makers, although most prefer to call their product "Tennessee whiskey" instead, including giant Jack Daniel's.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It is legally defined under Tennessee House Bill 1084, the North American Free Trade Agreement and at least one other international trade agreement as the recognized name for a straight bourbon whiskey produced in Tennessee.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It is also required to meet the legal definition of bourbon under Canadian law.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Although some Tennessee whiskey makers maintain that a pre-aging filtration through chunks of maple charcoal, known as the Lincoln County Process and legally mandated since 2013, make its flavor distinct from bourbon, U.S. regulations defining bourbon neither require nor prohibit its use.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon also was and is made in other U.S. states.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] To be legally sold as bourbon, the whiskey's mash bill requires a minimum of 51% corn, with the remainder being any cereal grain.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] A proposed change to U.S. regulations will expand allowable "grains" to include seeds of the pseudocereals amaranth, buckwheat, and quinoa.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] A mash bill that contains wheat instead of rye produces what is known as a wheated bourbon.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The grain is ground and mixed with water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Usually mash from a previous distillation is added to ensure consistency across batches, creating a sour mash.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Finally, yeast is added, and the mash is fermented.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It is distilled to (typically) between 65% and 80% alcohol using either a traditional alembic (or pot still) or the much less expensive continuous still.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Most modern bourbons are initially run off using a column still and then redistilled in a "doubler" (alternatively known as a "thumper" or "retort") that is basically a pot still.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The resulting clear spirit, called "white dog", is placed in charred new oak containers for aging.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In practice, these containers are generally barrels made from American white oak.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The spirit gains its color and much of its flavor from the caramelized sugars and vanillins in the charred wood.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Straight bourbon must be aged at least two years, and blended bourbon must contain at least 51% straight bourbon on a proof gallon basis (i.e., most of the alcohol in the blend must be from straight bourbon).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbons gain more color and flavor the longer they age in wood.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Changes to the spirit also occur due to evaporation and chemical processes such as oxidation.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Lower-priced bourbons tend to be aged relatively briefly.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Even for higher-priced bourbons, "maturity" rather than a particular age duration is often the goal, as over-aging bourbons can negatively affect the flavor of the bourbon (making it taste woody, bitter, or unbalanced).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] The remainder of the spirits in a blended bourbon may be neutral grain spirits that are not aged at all.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] If a product is labeled merely as bourbon whiskey rather than straight or blended, no specific minimum aging period is prescribed – only that the product has been "stored at not more than 62.5% alcohol by volume (125 proof) in charred new oak containers".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] After maturing, bourbon is withdrawn from the barrel and is typically filtered and diluted with water.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It is then bottled at no less than 80 US proof (40% abv).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Although most bourbon whiskey is sold at 80 proof, bourbon can be bottled much higher.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] All "bottled in bond" bourbon is 100 proof.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Some higher-proof bottlings are marketed as "barrel proof" or "cask strength", meaning they have not been diluted or have been only slightly diluted (less than 1% ABV dilution) after removal from the barrels.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon whiskey may be sold at less than 80 proof but must be labeled as "diluted bourbon".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] A very small number of bourbon bottlings have been released with exceptionally high proof, sometimes exceeding 140 proof (70% ABV).
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] In the mid-2010s, some sources began referring to these as "hazmat" bourbons, alluding to the ban in the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Code of Federal Regulations on air travel passengers and crew members carrying such high-proof beverages due to their highly flammable nature.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Such high proof levels are very uncommon even among "barrel proof" bourbons, as bourbon must enter the barrel at no higher than 125 proof and thus can only reach higher concentrations by disproportionate evaporation of water in the Angel's share during aging.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] After processing, barrels remain saturated with up to 10 U.S. gallons (38 liters) of bourbon, although 2–3 U.S. gallons (8–11 liters) is the norm.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] They may not be reused for bourbon, and most are sold to distilleries in Canada, Scotland, Ireland, Mexico, and the Caribbean for aging other spirits.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Some are employed in the manufacture of various barrel-aged products, including amateur and professionally brewed bourbon barrel-aged beer, barbecue sauce, wine, hot sauce, and others.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Since 2011, Jim Beam has employed barrel rinsing on a large scale to extract bourbon from its used barrels, mixing the extract with a 6-year-old Beam bourbon to create a 90-proof product that it sells as "Devil's Cut".
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] By itself, the phrase "bottled by" means only that.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Only if the bottler operates the distillery that produced the whiskey may "distilled by" be added to the label.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Labeling requirements for bourbon and other alcoholic beverages (including the requirements for what is allowed to be called bourbon under U.S. law) are defined in the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] No whiskey made outside the U.S. may be labeled bourbon or sold as bourbon inside the U.S.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Various other countries have trade agreements with the U.S. to recognize bourbon as a distinctive product of the U.S., including Canada and Mexico, the United Kingdom, Chile, and Brazil.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] A 2016 experiment by Louisville craft distiller Jefferson's Bourbon suggests that in the era before whiskey was routinely bottled at the distillery, Kentucky bourbon developed a superior taste because it was shipped in barrels, using water transport wherever practical.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] To test this theory, Jefferson's cofounder Trey Zoeller sent two barrels of the company's signature product to New York City via barge, first down the Ohio and Mississippi Rivers and then along the Intracoastal Waterway.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] As a control, he brought a batch of the same whiskey that had remained in Louisville during the same period.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] According to *Popular Mechanics* writer Jacqueline Detwiler-George, who documented the test, the sample that made the waterborne journey "was mature beyond its age, richer, with new flavors of tobacco, vanilla, caramel, and honey.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It was some of the best bourbon any of us had ever drunk." It was theorized that the action of gentle sloshing of the whiskey in barrels for a period of 2 to 4 weeks during the barge trip led to a dramatic improvement in smoothness and taste.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Chemical analysis of the two samples revealed significant differences in molecular profiles, with the sample transported by water having a greater diversity of aromatic compounds.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon is served in a variety of manners, including neat; diluted with water; over ice ("on the rocks"); with cola or other beverages in simple mixed drinks; and in cocktails – including the Manhattan, the Old Fashioned, the whiskey sour, and the mint julep.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon is also used in cooking, and it was historically used for medicinal purposes.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] Bourbon can be used in a variety of confections such as a banana bourbon syrup for waffles, a flavoring for chocolate cake, and fruit-based desserts like grilled peach sundaes served with salted bourbon-caramel, or brown sugar shortcake with warmed bourbon peaches.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It is an optional ingredient in several pie recipes traditional to American cuisine, including pumpkin pie, where it can be combined with brown sugar and pecans to make a sweet and crunchy topping for the creamy pumpkin pie filling.
[src:bourbon-whiskey/bourbon-whiskey] It can also be used as a flavoring in sauces for savory dishes like grit cakes with country ham served with bourbon mayonnaise, Kentucky bourbon chili, and grilled flank steak.
